The fifth Eclogue is a very close and very ingenious imitation of Virgil's eighth. In each poem there are two songs, one describing the grief of a ‹lespairing lover sor the saithlessness os his mistress. the other. the efforts of a sorsaken girl to secure her lover’s return by enchantments. Here. as in VirgiL each song is divided into ten stanzas of different lengths separated from one another by a resrain. And here, as in virgil, the first seven stanzas of the second song cor— respond exactly in length to the first seven stanzas of the other. The poem shows also the influence os Theocritus; see the notes on lines 30-33‚ 60-61‚ 67-68, 76-78.
